      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Harris Kupperman Is Calling the Top of the AI Semiconductor Trade</h2>

      <p>Legendary macro strategist Harris Kupperman (Kuppy) is flashing red on his proprietary exhaustion models.</p>

      <p>This isn't a subtle signal. This is a direct call: the AI semiconductor momentum trade is topping. What happens next is a rotation into crypto.</p>

      <p>Jordi Visser is relaying the critical details of Kuppy's thesis, and it's worth understanding because it identifies the specific inflection point where the trade rolls over.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">The Exhaustion Model Is Flashing Red</h2>

      <p>Kuppy has a proprietary exhaustion indicator that tracks candlestick reversal patterns — the technical signatures of intense buying and selling pressure battles.</p>

      <p>When these patterns appear consecutively, it signals momentum is running out of steam.</p>

      <p>"Nothing has changed enough for this to be a ninebagger in that short amount of time. The exhaustion model's been tested... average move 4.1, it's exactly there."</p>

      <p>Translation: semiconductor stocks have gone up 9x in months. Fundamentally, nothing justifies that magnitude of move in that timeframe. The exhaustion model says we're at the inflection point.</p>

      <p>What happens at inflection? Volatility explodes. Either massive continuation or violent reversal.</p>

      <p>The signal is so clear that Korean and French semiconductor names are already showing candlestick reversal patterns — international smart money rotating out.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">The Supply Chain Catalyst: Hormuz Closure</h2>

      <p>This is the fundamental trigger that could break the AI trade. Not demand destruction. Supply destruction.</p>

      <p>The Strait of Hormuz handles 20% of global oil flows. A closure doesn't just create energy shortages — it creates petrochemical shortages.</p>

      <p>Semiconductors require specialized chemicals: photoresists, dopants, advanced materials for packaging and cooling. These come from petrochemical supplies.</p>

      <p>"The Strait of Hormuz being shut down is an April event. We're going to be out of, believe it or not, motor oil in the next couple weeks. Exxon and Shell inform major suppliers, including Costco, to prepare for empty shelves."</p>

      <p>This creates a "good news is bad news" scenario:</p>

      <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-300 ml-4">
        <li>AI demand remains strong</li>
        <li>But supply gets constrained by petrochemical shortages</li>
        <li>Companies can't fulfill orders</li>
        <li>Inventory builds up</li>
        <li>Margins compress</li>
        <li>Earnings misses from production constraints, not demand weakness</li>
      </ul>

      <p>This is how you break a momentum trade — not with demand destruction, but with supply destruction that creates margin compression exactly when everyone expects earnings growth.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Institutional Momentum Chasing at Peak</h2>

      <p>This is the classic late-cycle signal that confirms Kuppy's call.</p>

      <p>"Our trading desk has seen sovereign wealth funds and asset managers getting stopped into this tape as buyers since the calendar flipped to May."</p>

      <p>Translation: institutional managers were structurally underweight AI (benchmark arbitrage). They lagged the move. Now they're panic-buying at the top to catch up to their benchmarks.</p>

      <p>This creates artificial demand that's unsustainable. Once momentum breaks, these forced buyers become forced sellers. The unwinding accelerates.</p>

      <p>For professional traders, this is the perfect setup: institutions are buying your inventory at peak prices. Let them.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">The Amazon Analog: 9x in 14 Years vs. 9x in 6 Months</h2>

      <p>Kuppy makes a critical distinction about the sustainability of this move.</p>

      <p>Amazon did a 9x move from 2006–2020. That's 14 years of justified fundamental growth. Semiconductors just did a 9x move in 6 months.</p>

      <p>The magnitude is eventually justified. The timeframe compression is not.</p>

      <p>"You could have called this a bubble from 2006 to 2020. The issue is not semi doing this... The issue is the time side that it did."</p>

      <p>This means one of two things happens:</p>

      <p><strong class="text-white">Option 1 — Time Correction:</strong> Semiconductors consolidate sideways for 1–2 years. The move continues but becomes sustainable.</p>

      <p><strong class="text-white">Option 2 — Price Correction:</strong> Semiconductors correct 30–50%. Then consolidate. Then continue higher over years.</p>

      <p>One way or another, the parabolic move needs to reset. The question is whether it resets with time or price.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">The Exhaustion Pattern: Candlestick Reversals Across International Names</h2>

      <p>This is the technical confirmation of Kuppy's fundamental call.</p>

      <p>Consecutive candlestick wicks (large intraday reversals) indicate intense battle between buyers and sellers. When these appear on multiple names simultaneously, it signals the buyers are losing.</p>

      <p>Korean semiconductor names showing reversals. French semiconductor names showing reversals. US names lagging.</p>

      <p>This is international smart money rotating out ahead of US retail and institutional momentum chasers. Classic late-cycle pattern.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">The DRAM Second Derivative Turning Negative</h2>

      <p>Here's the early warning signal that most investors are missing: DRAM pricing momentum is turning negative.</p>

      <p>Historically, when the DRAM second derivative rolls over, it precedes SOX (semiconductor ETF) underperformance.</p>

      <p>It's not DRAM prices going negative. It's the rate of change of DRAM prices turning negative. Subtle but critical difference. By the time DRAM prices actually fall, the move has already been repriced in charts.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">The Rotation: AI Momentum Out, Crypto In</h2>

      <p>Once the AI momentum unwind begins, where does the capital rotate? Crypto. Specifically Bitcoin and silver.</p>

      <p>Why? Because negative real yields are returning. Hard assets outperform financial assets. And Bitcoin has technically broken out and is approaching new territory.</p>

      <p>Kuppy's positioning: scale out of AI momentum immediately. Rotate into Bitcoin and silver on weakness.</p>

      <p>The timeline: this could happen in the next 3–6 months, or momentum could extend another 6–12 months on pure institutional FOMO. The risk is being early — or missing the crypto parabola entirely if rotation happens faster than expected.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">Speed Crashes and Volatility Expansion</h2>

      <p>When momentum trades unwind, they don't unwind gradually. They speed crash.</p>

      <p>Volatility expands. Drawdowns happen fast. Recovery can be equally fast — especially if driven by AI agents that don't carry human emotion.</p>

      <p>This is why position sizing and hedges matter. The move could be 15% down in days, not weeks.</p>

      <hr class="border-white/10 my-10" />

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-white mt-10 mb-4">What This Means</h2>

      <p>Harris Kupperman is calling the top of the AI semiconductor trade.</p>

      <p>Not saying it's a bad investment long-term. Saying it's exhausted in the short-term and the momentum will reverse.</p>

      <p>The catalyst is Hormuz supply chain disruption creating margin compression exactly when everyone expects earnings growth. The confirmation is international smart money already rotating out via candlestick reversals.</p>

      <p>The play: exit AI momentum, wait for the correction, rotate into Bitcoin and crypto on weakness, then position for the next leg higher once consolidation completes.</p>

      <p>The timeline is uncertain. Could be weeks. Could be months. But the exhaustion model is flashing red.</p>

